"The sea is ours": Bolivia, a landlocked country, hopes the court will reopen its path to the Pacific
Sailors patrol a rope-covered naval base in La Paz.
Public buildings bear a navy-blue flag.
The naval bases of Lake Titicaca for the Amazon bear the motto: "The sea is ours by right.
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout landlocked Bolivia, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century is still alive, as is the yearning to sail once again in the Pacific Ocean.
Those hopes are perhaps at the highest point in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice on Oct. 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, a positive outlook on the outcome,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the ruling of the ICJ on giant screens scattered throughout the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will rule in favor of their country’s claim, so that, after decades of uncertain negotiations, Chile will be forced to negotiate, granting Bolivia a sovereign outlet to the sea.
Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president, Evo Morales, who faces a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has a lot at stake in Monday’s ruling.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” the president said last August.
However, some analysts believe it is unlikely that the court will rule in favor of Bolivia, and that little would change even if it did not.
The UN body, based in the Netherlands, has no power to allocate Chilean territory to another country and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the IJC sentence is delivered only six months after hearing the final allegations indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And far from promoting the Bolivian cause, the past four years may have hurt it.
"The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
Morales’ belligerent rhetoric undermined some residual Chilean goodwill, he suggested.
At some point in the future, Bolivia and Chile will continue the talks, but it will be extremely difficult to maintain the dialogue after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision-making process was unusually fast.
Next Monday will give Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to begin a new era of relations with Chile" and a possibility to "put an end to 139 years of mutually beneficial disagreements," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents, was using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The sentence is an opportunity to understand that we have to go beyond the past.”
