North Korea says 'not to think' of unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were aggravating mistrust of the United States and that there was no way for the country to unilaterally dispense with its nuclear weapons in these circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body's annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant measures of goodwill" last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test center and committing to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technologies.
"However, we do not see any corresponding response from the United States," he said.
“Without confidence in the U.S., there will be no confidence in our national security, and in such circumstances there is no way for us to proceed with our disarmament first.”
While Ri has recycled well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded as it took gradual steps, his statements appear to be significant in that they do not in the first instance reject unilateral denuclearization, in contrast to Pyongyang’s previous positions.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a U.S. president in office and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump offered security assurances to North Korea.
North Korea has been seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean war, but the United States says Pyongyang must first abandon its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to soften tough international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive way, opposing even the 'declaration of an end to war'," Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the extension of sanctions is aggravating our suspicion.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the stakeholder on this issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have come to this impasse.”
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was drastically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that steering North Korea’s rockets toward U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. Mau” Trump called Kim the “rocket man” on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year had threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps toward disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until North Korea’s denuclearization.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timetable for it, saying “whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The implementation of the Security Council sanctions must vigorously continue until denuclearization is complete, final and verifiable.”
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea imposed since 2006 in a bid to strangle funding for North Korea's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but the last visit did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, although North Korea later denounced him for "making gangster demands.
In a meeting with Moon earlier this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile facility and also a nuclear complex if the United States “takes corresponding action.”
Pompeo said Kim had told him that the “corresponding measures” they were seeking were the security guarantees assumed by Trump in Singapore, as well as initiatives to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students attend course that teaches them to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has put all its students to sleep more, in an initiative to combat the macho culture of studying in caffeinated “directs.”
One professor concluded that students at the university at the top of the world rankings often had no idea about the most basic concepts about self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and an expert at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the U.S.
The inspiration for the course came after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end, a girl came to me and said, 'Why are you just telling me this in the last year of the course?'
The young woman stated that no one had ever mentioned to her the importance of sleep, which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts about how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance, as well as to improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the institution decided to introduce the course after concluding that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a dormitory where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, sneakers and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are briefed on how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of stroke, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus map, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it won’t change the behavior of students instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know, just as we all have a right to know the health effects of the smoking option,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “making direct” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students makes this a growing problem.
Ensuring that we get enough quality sleep should be a “secret weapon” for students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid getting fat, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in hunger mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler conceive the course after attending one of his classes last year in his first year at Harvard.
The course opened his eyes and inspired him to encourage the creation of a campus-wide course, he said.
The next step, according to their expectations, is to ask all graduate students to attend a similar program of study before entering the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students consider using an alarm when going to bed, as well as when waking up, and be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can dysregulate circadian rhythm and lead to problems falling asleep.
