Almanaque: the inventor of the Geiger counter
And now a page of our "Sunday Morning" Almanac: On September 30, 1882, he is now 136 years old and continues to TELL ... the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A fundamental piece of science since then, the Geiger accountant has also become a central element of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado" in which the unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans participated:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals like a uranium.
When we put these headphones on, we can even hear the effects of the atoms released by radioactivity in the minerals.”
Evans: "Look, it's crackling right now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
