What is the Global Citizen Festival? Did you do anything to reduce poverty?
On Saturday, New York City will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event featuring an extremely impressive list of stars who will perform on an equally impressive mission: to eradicate poverty in the world.
Already in its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival will welcome tens of thousands of people to the Great Central Park Lawn, not only to watch performances such as those of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to raise awareness of the true goal of the event: to eradicate extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, launched in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, a advocacy group that hopes to end poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To receive a free ticket to the event (unless they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket) viewers had to perform a series of tasks, or “actions”, such as volunteering, sending an email to a world leader, a phone call or any other significant ways that contribute to raising awareness for the purpose of ending poverty.
However, what has been the degree of success of the Global Citizen in these 12 years in achieving its goal?
