Global Citizen claims that since 2011, it has recorded more than 19 million “actions” from its supporters that have exerted pressure to achieve a number of different goals.
These actions, according to the organization, have contributed to world leaders having announced commitments and policies valued at more than $37 billion, which will affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements arising from its actions, with at least $10 billion of them already disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that the funds raised so far have had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people around the world.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based partnership bringing together investors and implementers committed to “helping children reach their full potential,” which has pledged to give Rwanda $35 million to help end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 tweets from Global Citizens.
“With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens like all of us, we can make the social injustice of malnutrition a footnote of history,” Tracey Ullman, ambassador for The Power of Nutrition, told a crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that after more than 5,000 pressure actions on the UK to improve mothers’ and children’s nutrition, the government announced that it would fund a project, the Power of Nutrition, which will cover 5 million women and children, with interventions at the level of nutrition.
In response to one of the website's frequently asked questions, "What makes you think we can eradicate extreme poverty?"
The Global Citizen replies, “It’s been a long, tortuous road — sometimes we fall and fail.
But, like the great civil rights and anti-apartheid movements that preceded us, because we are more powerful together.
