The inventor of the World Wide Web intends to create a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, has created a startup that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project by this legendary tech character, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee’s open source platform, Solid.
This allows users to decide where their data is stored and who has access to what information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokingly stated that Inrupt's underlying intention is to "dominate the world."
“We have to do it now,” he said of the startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “personal online data warehouse,” or POD.
It may contain contact lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It’s as if Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify are all available in one browser at the same time.
What is unique about online personal data storage is that it is solely up to the user to decide who has access to what type of information.
The company calls it “personal empowerment through data.”
Inrupt’s idea, according to the company’s CEO John Bruce, is to provide the right resources, processes and skills to help make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, some in-house programmers hired to work on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology creators around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a total change in which all their business models are turned upside down overnight.
“We’re not asking for permission.”
In a publication in Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s “mission is to create commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new Web created with Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate over internet neutrality.
Even as he launches Inrupt, Berners-Lee will continue to be founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic about this next era of the Web,” added Berners-Lee.
Bernard Vann: Tribute to the Clergyman Awarded the Victoria Cross in the First Great War
The only Church of England clergyman to receive the Victoria Cross during the First Great War as a fighter was honored in his hometown after 100 years.
The Lieutenant-Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann obtained the decoration on 29 September 1918 with the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later and never knew that he received the highest British military honor.
Her two grandchildren uncovered a commemorative plaque at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of them, Michael Vann, said it was “brilliantly symbolic” that the plaque had been presented exactly 100 years after the deed that gave the decoration to his grandfather.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Saint-Quentin Canal "in a very thick fog and under close fire of portable weapons and machine guns".
He then ran to the line of fire and, "with the greatest courage," led the line forward before attacking a cannon alone and shooting down three soldiers of the detachment.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I could never match, but also a lesson in humility.”
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, deposited a wreath after the parade, led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he was "very honored to participate in the parade" and added that "the bravery of a genuine hero is to be demonstrated through the support that will be given by many people."
