In an interview with Radio 4's first Desert Island Discs hosted by Lauren Laverne, he said he had spoken out in favor of gay rights to give "hope" to others.
He also claimed that becoming a father made him worry less about winning the Olympics.
The show’s longtime regular host, Kirsty Young, took a several-month break due to illness.
Appearing as an outcast on Laverne's first show, Daley noted that he felt "inferior" to all the others because "it was not socially acceptable to like boys and girls".
“To this day, that impression of feeling smaller and different has been the real reason that gave me the power and strength to succeed.”
His goal was to prove that he was “someone,” he said, so as not to disappoint everyone when they discovered their sexuality sooner or later.
The double Olympic bronze medalist has become a prominent LGBT activist and has used his participation in this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
According to him, he expressed why he was happy to be able to live openly without consequences and intended to give “hope” to others.
The three-time world champion said falling in love with a man, American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013, “took me by surprise.”
Daley married the Oscar winner last year, 20 years his senior, although he said the age difference was never a problem.
"When we go through so much when we're so young" - his first Olympic participation was at the age of 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he said, it's hard to find someone of the same age who has gone through similar ups and downs.
The couple had a son last June, named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley said "the whole outlook" had changed.
“If you had asked me last year, all that mattered was ‘earning a gold medal,’” he said.
"But you know, there are bigger things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.”
His son bears the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Daley said his father did not accept the fact that he was going to die and one of the last things he asked was if they already had tickets to the London 2012 games because he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him ‘you’re not going to be around to be in the front row, Dad,’” he said.
“I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing and it was only when he really stopped breathing and died that I finally recognized that he was not invincible,” he said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
“I was fully aware that this was what I had dreamed of all my life: diving in front of a crowd of compatriots at the Olympics ... there was no better feeling,” he said.
All this was also the inspiration for his first song choice - Proud, by Heather Small - with which he had identified during the preparation for the Olympics, and which still gives him chicken skin.
