New German warship once again postponed
The latest German navy frigate was expected to enter service in 2014 to replace Cold War-era warships, but it will need to wait at least until next year, due to systems prone to failure and an exponentially growing cost, according to local media.
The entry into service of the "Rheinland-Pfalz", the command ship of the brand new frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class, has now been postponed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit which quoted a military spokesman.
The vessel was supposed to join the navy in 2014, but troubling post-delivery problems undermined the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels that the navy had commissioned in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is known that they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, as well as a series of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies such as the reduction of radar, infrared and acoustic signatures.
Other important features include longer periods between maintenance, which would allow sending the latest frigates on missions with a maximum duration of two years away from the ports of origin.
However, continued delays have meant that state-of-the-art warships, seen as a way for Germany to project power across borders, will be out of date when they enter service, Die Zeit reports.
The unfortunate F125 made headlines last year when the German navy refused to put it into service, having returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the navy returned a ship to the shipyard after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media cites a number of crucial "hardware and software defects" that would make the warship useless if used in a combat mission.
Software shortcomings were particularly important, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, only half the contingent needed on the oldest Bremen-class frigates.
It is also known that the vessel is excessively heavy, which reduces its performance and limits the ability of the navy to install additional functionalities in the future.
The 7000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz is believed to have twice the weight of ships of similar classes used by the Germans in World War II.
In addition to hardware failures, the price of the entire project, including crew training, is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached a staggering EUR 3.1 billion, an increase from the EUR 2.2 billion initially budgeted.
The problems plaguing the latest frigates have become particularly important in light of recent warnings that German naval power is weakening.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliamentary defence committee, acknowledged that the navy is currently running out of ships capable of being used.
The problem has grown exponentially over time as older ships have been put out of service without vessels to replace them.
In the end, he regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class had been able to join the navy.
The National Trust spies on the secret lives of bats
New research is underway on a property in the Scottish Highlands to reveal how bats use the landscape to search for food.
The results are expected to shed some light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide conservation activities in the future.
The study, carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common and fruit bats, as well as the long-eared browns and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations scattered throughout the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
Mobile studies will also be carried out by NTS staff and volunteers with portable detectors.
Expert analysis of all recordings will assess the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of their behaviors at the territorial scale.
Rob Dewar, NTS nature conservation adviser, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as grassland creation, as well as the best way to maintain forests for bats and associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the past century.
These animals are threatened by the construction and development work that affect the dormitories and make the habitat scarce.
Wind turbines and lightning are also a threat, along with fly-killing papers and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to attacks from domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, given your nocturnal hunting habits, your ears are more useful than your eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo location technique to identify insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the region, takes bats very seriously.
The organization has ten trained experts who regularly carry out studies, inspections of dormitories and sometimes rescues.
He also created the first reserve in Scotland dedicated exclusively to bats, at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which houses eight of the ten species of Scottish bats.
The director of the property, David Thompson, says it is the ideal territory for them.
“Here at Threave we have an excellent area for bats,” he said.
“We have the old buildings, a lot of old trees and all this good habitat.
However, there’s still a lot about bats that we don’t know about, so the work we’ve done here and on the other properties will help us learn more about what they need to flourish.”
He stressed the importance of checking for bats before performing maintenance on the properties, because the unintentional destruction of only one maternity dormitory can lead to the death of up to 400 females and young animals, which could eradicate the entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their dormitories.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to participate to help.
“We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many of our species, we just don’t know how their populations are taking revenge.”
