The European National Team beats the U.S. and wins the 2018 Ryder Cup with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National on the outskirts of Paris, France.
The U.S. has now accumulated six consecutive losses on European soil since the last time it won the Ryder Cup in Europe in 1993.
Europe is once again crowned victorious after the team of Danish captain Thomas Bjorn reached the 14.5 points they needed to beat the United States.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who proved to have serious difficulties during almost the entire tournament, threw the starting tee into the water in hole 16, par 3, giving the victory to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari has shined in all of his rounds, becoming one of four players to score 5-0-0 since the current format of the tournament began in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth lost 5&4 to the worst-ranked player of the European national team, Thorbjorn Olesen of Denmark.
The world’s top-ranked player, Dustin Johnson, lost 2-1 to Ian Poulter of England in what may have been his last Ryder Cup appearance.
A veteran of eight Ryder Cups, the Spaniard Sergio Garcia has become the most awarded European of all tournaments with 25.5 career points.
“It’s not my habit to cry, but today I couldn’t contain myself.
It's been a tough year.
I can't help but thank Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm so glad we won the cup.
It was all a team effort and I’m happy to have been able to help,” Garcia said after the European victory.
He gives the floor to his compatriot Jon Rham who defeated American golf legend Tiger Woods by 2&1 in singles on Sunday.
"It's impossible to describe the pride I feel for defeating Tiger Woods. I grew up watching him play," said 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all four games in France and now has a 13-21-3 record in the Ryder Cup.
Unusual statistical values of one of the greatest players of all time with 14 great titles won and only beaten by Jack Nicklaus.
With the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau who had a high-calibre performance throughout the tournament, the rest of the U.S. National Team struggled to make it to the fairway.
U.S. Captain Jim Furyk spoke after his team's disappointing performance. "I'm proud of them. They fought.
This morning, we managed to put some fear in Europe.
We fought.
Congratulations to Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players were excellent.
We will reorganize and work with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup Commission to move forward.
I like a lot of these 12 players and I’m proud to be their captain.
I have to take the hat off the other team.
They were better."
Updated Red Tide Information: Concentrations Decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there has been a decrease in Red Tide concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of less proliferation of spots were identified in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Tide spot extends about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
The Red Tide was also spotted in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations were recorded near or off the coast of Pinella County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations near or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations near or off the coast of Col County, Lower Le County, and off the coast of Collier County.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
In the past week, there have been no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwestern region of Florida.
